status_message:
We are deeply saddened to learn of the death of David Miller, a College of Biological Sciences student, who has been missing since Tuesday, May 10. Our thoughts are with David's family, friends, classmates, and others in the University community who are grieving. The University of Minnesota Police Department appreciates the support from several local agencies in searching for David during the last week.

From Danita Brown Young, vice provost for student affairs and dean of students: "This is a difficult and sad time for our University community. David will be missed by many. Counseling and support services for any students, faculty and staff who may need it continue to be available. Counselors at Boynton Health Service and Student Counseling Services are available for in-person, individual appointments. Walk-ins are welcome between 8 a.m. ‚Äì 4:30 p.m. A U of M, 24/7 crisis line can be reached at 612-301-4673."

Update on search for David Miller:
University of Minnesota Police and the University's Office for Student Affairs continue to work closely with the family of David Miller and the local agencies that have helped search for David, who has been missing since Tuesday. The campus community sends its hopes that David is found safe and sound. While no additional information is available at this time, we ask the public and media to respect the privacy of David's family and friends, as well as the ongoing search process.
 
During this time of need, support and counseling is available to any members of the University community who need it. Students are encouraged to contact Boynton Health Service (http://www.bhs.umn.edu/east-bank-clinic/mental-health-services.htm) or Student Counseling Services (http://uccs.umn.edu/appointments.htm) for assistance.
 
If you have any information about David's whereabouts, please call UMPD at 612-624-COPS (612-624-2677) or dial 911.

Extreme swings in blood sugar, which some people who have type 1 diabetes experience despite specialized care from medical professionals, can be life-threatening.

status_message:
Throwback Thursday: In 1908, researchers at the University of Minnesota were #UMNdriven to develop hardy apple trees for our northern climate, so they created the Fruit Breeding Farm on 80 acres near Victoria, MN. Since then, more than 98 fruit introductions have been made, including the well-known (and well-loved) Honeycrisp apple! Today, it is now known as the Minnesota Landscape Arboretum Horticultural Research Center (HRC). Additional activities at the HRC include breeding landscape plants, plant cold-hardiness research, and restoration ecology research. 

(Photos courtesy of the University of Minnesota Archives)

"We're part of homeland security, only we protect your dinner." --Dr. Amy Kircher

Kircher and her team at the Food Protection and Defense Institute are #UMNdriven to make sure the global food supply is kept safe from potential threats. The institute--set up at the University of Minnesota after 9/11--is an action-oriented research consortium that addresses the vulnerability of the nation's food system, from farms and transportation to food processing, retail, and food service.
link_name: What drives Amy Kircher to protect America's food?

status_message:
Throughout his lifetime, alumnus Norman Borlaug was #UMNdriven to help end world hunger. Today, the state of Minnesota celebrates Norman E. Borlaug Day to commemorate his outstanding service to Minnesota and the rest of the world.

Borlaug's work on new agricultural techniques and high-yield crop breeding averted mass famines, significantly increased global food security, and ultimately sparked the Green Revolution. Nicknamed "The Man Who Saved A Billion Lives," Borlaug was awarded the Nobel Peace Prize in 1970 in recognition for his contributions to world peace through improved food security. You can read more about his amazing legacy at https://www.cfans.umn.edu/borlaug.

This Sunday, the University of Minnesota Solar Vehicle Project will compete in the 2015 World Solar Challenge. Join us in wishing the team good luck!

The UMN Solar Vehicle Project has a great history of success: this is the team's 25th year, and they have gained numerous accolades, including a 2nd place win in the 2014 American Solar Challenge. This year, the #UMN team is the only United States team competing in the Cruiser class, and is among only 7 U.S. teams competing in the entire World Solar Challenge.

status_message:
This week, #UMN participated in Governor Mark Dayton's trade delegation to Mexico. One of the goals of the trip was to strengthen ties in government, commerce, education, and culture.

Meredith McQuaid, dean of international programs, said, "I'm proud to have represented the University on this important trade delegation. Mexico is not only one of Minnesota's largest trading partners, but it is our neighbor. I'm hopeful that the relationships built during this trip will strengthen our ties with Mexico now and for years to come."

Dean McQuaid also had a chance to meet with Jalisco State Minister of Innovation and proud #UMN alumnus Jaime Reyes Robles (Master's Degree in Chemical Engineering, 1970), pictured below.

status_message:
Exciting news from the College of Biological Sciences! The Amorphophallus titanium (aka the "Corpse plant") is sending up its first ever inflorescence. This time around the flower will not reach its full potential, but it will still be an impressive sight! See it at room 19, CBS Greenhouse, 1534 Lindig St. St. Paul.
Facts: A mature bloom can reach up to 7-12 feet in height, and a diameter of 3-4 feet; The bloom will last only 1-3 days; the "stinking" odor lasts only the first 8 hours the bloom is open; a mature leaf can reach up to 20 feet in height and 15 feet in diameter; a mature tuber can weigh up to 120-170 pounds.
http://greenhouses.cfans.umn.edu/Plant_Collection.html
More on Wikipedia: http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Titan_arum
